om","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"ap","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Dutch: occupational name for a cobbler.","Slovenian: nickname for a talkative person, from <i>lapati</i> ‘to babble’, or a topographic name from dialect <i>lap</i> ‘abyss’. Compare   Lapp   4."],"variants":[{"name":"Lapp","meanings":["German, English, and Dutch: from Middle High German and Middle English <i>lappe</i>, Middle Dutch <i>lap</i> ‘cloth, patch, rag’, a metonymic occupational name for a mender of clothes or shoes, or a nickname given to someone who wore ragged clothes or garments with loose folds, flaps, or hanging sleeves, or who had fleshy folds of skin on his face, neck, or body.","German: nickname for a simple-minded person, from Middle Low German <i>lappe</i> ‘fool’. This surname (in any of the two possible senses; see also 1 above) is also found in France (mainly Alsace, also Lorraine).","English: nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>lappe</i> ‘burdock’, perhaps for someone with a prickly character."]}]},{"name":"Nicolas","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alberto, Angelito, Emilio, Fernando, Francisco, Manuel, Mario, Ricardo, Rodolfo, Ruben, Alfredo, Angel.  French Luc, Pierre, Andre, Georges, Jacques, Marcellin, Yves, Adrien, Alain, Camille, Celina, Dominique.","Spanish (<b>Nicolás</b>), French, Walloon, Breton, and West Indian (mainly Haiti): from the personal name <i>Nicolás</i> (Spanish), <i>Nicolas</i> (French, Breton), from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i> (see   Nicholas  ). In France, this surname is most common in Brittany.","English (southern England and Glamorgan): variant of   Nicholas  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nicole","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Elzear.","French: from the personal name <i>Nicole</i>, feminine form of   Nicolas  .","English (Middlesex): variant of   Nichol  ."]},{"name":"Loesel","meanings":["German (<b>Lösel</b>): from a pet form of the personal name <i>Nikolaus</i>, German form of   Nicolas  ."]},{"name":"Nykiel","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Polish Zbigniew, Stanislaw.","Polish: from the personal name <i>Nicolaus</i>, the Latin form of   Nicolas   (Polish <i>Mikołaj</i>), or a Polonized form of German   Nickel  ."]},{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]}]},{"name":"Iorwerth","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: from <i>iōr</i>‘ ‘lord’ + a mutated form of <i>berth</i> ‘handsome’; borne in the <i>Mabinogi</i> by the jealous brother of  Madawg , son of  Maredudd . <i>Iorwerth</i> came to be regarded as a Welsh equivalent of  Edward , but it has no actual connection with that name."],"variants":[{"name":"Yorath","meanings":["Anglicized form of   Iorwerth   or, in some cases, a transferred use of the surname derived from it."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Iorwerth ap Nicolas was born about 1244, in Glamorgan, Wales. She had at least 1 son with Iorwerth ap Nicolas."},"et":{"about 1244–":"umbes 1244–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1280–Male":"1280–Surnud","1244–Female":"1244–Surnud","1244":"1244","about 1244":"umbes 1244","1240":"1240","Abt 1280":"umbes 1280","1280":"1280","Morgannwg gwlad, Glamorganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1244–":"noin 1244–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1280–Male":"1280–Kuollut","1244–Female":"1244–Kuollut","1244":"1244","about 1244":"noin 1244","1240":"1240","Abt 1280":"noin 1280","1280":"1280","Morgannwg gwlad, Glamorganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales"},"fr":{"about 1244–":"environ 1244–Décédée","1240–Male":"1240–Décédé","1280–Male":"1280–Décédé","1244–Female":"1244–Décédée","1244":"1244","about 1244":"environ 1244","1240":"1240","Abt 1280":"environ 1280","1280":"1280","Morgannwg gwlad, Glamorganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Galles","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Iorwerth ap Nicolas est née environ 1244, à Glamorgan, Galles. Elle a eu au moins 1 fils avec Iorwerth ap Nicolas."},"de":{"about 1244–":"um 1244–Verstorben","1240–Male":"1240–Verstorben","1280–Male":"1280–Verstorben","1244–Female":"1244–Verstorben","1244":"1244","about 1244":"um 1244","1240":"1240","Abt 1280":"um 1280","1280":"1280","Morgannwg gwlad, Glamorganshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","Glamorgan, Wales":"Glamorgan, Wales","lifeSummary":"Mrs. Iorwerth ap Nicolas wurde um 1244 in Glamorgan, Wales geboren. Sie hatte mit Iorwerth ap Nicolas mindestens 1 Sohn."},"ht":{"about 1244–":"about 1244–Dese